<subSubSection pageId="23" pageNumber="24" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="23.[151,1437,978,1471]" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,315,1158,1183]" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">Remarks.</emphasis>
The external appearance and male genitalia of the examined specimens are clearly in agreement with Goater's (2005) statements, with the only exception of teeth on the ventral surface of gnathos. As stated by 
<bibRefCitation box="[151,314,1230,1255]" pageId="23" pageNumber="24" refId="ref19338" refString="Goater, B. (2005) Evergestinae. In: Goater, B., Nuss, M. &amp; W. Speidel, Pyraloidea I. In: P. Huemer &amp; O. Karsholt, Microlepidoptera of Europe 4. Apollo Books, Stenstrup, pp. 69 - 107, 182 - 183, 190 - 193, 208 - 223, 244 - 256." type="book chapter">Goater (2005)</bibRefCitation>
, a few faint indications of teeth present on the ventral surface of gnathos; while in the examined males, the small teeth at this area are distinct, extending from the apex to two-thirds of its length along the shaft (
<figureCitation box="[159,281,1302,1327]" captionStart="FIGURE 7" captionStartId="11.[151,250,1948,1970]" captionTargetBox="[156,1387,509,1917]" captionTargetId="figure@11.[151,1436,445,1927]" captionTargetPageId="11" captionText="FIGURE 7. Male genitalia. A, D, G) Evergestis comealis stat. n. B, E, H) E. shirazalis, Paratype. C, F, I) E. infirmalis. A, B, C: main body and phallus. D, E, F: posterior end including uncus and gnathos in lateral (D, F) and ventral (E) views. G, H, I: distal end of phallus." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1247148/files/figure.png" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">Figs 7C, F</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="23.[151,1437,978,1471]" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">
This species could be distinguished from 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Herrich-Schaffer" baseAuthorityYear="1840" box="[685,818,1339,1363]" class="Insecta" family="Crambidae" genus="Evergestis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="23" pageNumber="24" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="caesialis">
<emphasis box="[685,818,1339,1363]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">E. caesialis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Amsel" baseAuthorityYear="1961" box="[879,1014,1339,1363]" class="Insecta" family="Crambidae" genus="Evergestis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="23" pageNumber="24" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="comealis">
<emphasis box="[879,1014,1339,1363]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">E. comealis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by the shape of uncus and gnathos, dentition of gnathos, and shape of cornuti (
<figureCitation box="[627,740,1374,1399]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="4.[151,250,1901,1923]" captionTargetBox="[175,1430,199,1872]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[151,1436,193,1879]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURE 2. Male genitalia. A–D) Evergestis affinis, Paratype (♂). E–J) E. caesialis. A, E: main body and phallus. B, H: posterior end including uncus and gnathos in lateral (B) and ventral (H) view. C, J: anterior end including juxta and vinculum. D, I: distal end of phallus. F: posterior end including uncus and anal tube. G: posterior end including gnathos and valva." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1247138/files/figure.png" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">Figs 2E–I</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[751,932,1375,1399]" captionStart="FIGURE 7" captionStartId="11.[151,250,1948,1970]" captionTargetBox="[156,1387,509,1917]" captionTargetId="figure@11.[151,1436,445,1927]" captionTargetPageId="11" captionText="FIGURE 7. Male genitalia. A, D, G) Evergestis comealis stat. n. B, E, H) E. shirazalis, Paratype. C, F, I) E. infirmalis. A, B, C: main body and phallus. D, E, F: posterior end including uncus and gnathos in lateral (D, F) and ventral (E) views. G, H, I: distal end of phallus." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1247148/files/figure.png" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">7A, C, D, F, G, I</figureCitation>
). In 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Staudinger" baseAuthorityYear="1870" box="[983,1122,1374,1398]" class="Insecta" family="Crambidae" genus="Evergestis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="23" pageNumber="24" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="infirmalis">
<emphasis box="[983,1122,1374,1398]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">E. infirmalis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, uncus is duck-beak-shaped with the tip being slightly upturned, and the toothless end of gnathos is shorter than that of 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Amsel" baseAuthorityYear="1961" box="[1162,1293,1411,1435]" class="Insecta" family="Crambidae" genus="Evergestis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="23" pageNumber="24" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="comealis">
<emphasis box="[1162,1293,1411,1435]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">E. comealis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation captionStart="FIGURE 7" captionStartId="11.[151,250,1948,1970]" captionTargetBox="[156,1387,509,1917]" captionTargetId="figure@11.[151,1436,445,1927]" captionTargetPageId="11" captionText="FIGURE 7. Male genitalia. A, D, G) Evergestis comealis stat. n. B, E, H) E. shirazalis, Paratype. C, F, I) E. infirmalis. A, B, C: main body and phallus. D, E, F: posterior end including uncus and gnathos in lateral (D, F) and ventral (E) views. G, H, I: distal end of phallus." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1247148/files/figure.png" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">Figs 7A, C, D, F</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
